07761nam a22010935i 9783110686647DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106866477 a10.1515/97831106866472doi  a(DE-B1597)541275  a(OCoLC)1202624505  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP285 7aLAN0090002bisacsh00aComplex Adpositions in European Languages :bA Micro-Typological Approach to Complex Nominal Relators /ced. by Benjamin Fagard, José Pinto de Lima, Dejan Stosic, Elena Smirnova. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (X, 400 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEmpirical Approaches to Language Typology [EALT] ,x0933-761X ;v6500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Complex adpositions and complex nominal relators -- tIndo-European language families & isolates -- t1 Complex adpositions in Romance: Emergence and variation -- t2 Complex adpositions in three West Germanic Languages: German, Dutch, and English -- t3 Complex adpositions in Slavic languages: The case of Serbian -- t4 Complex prepositions in Breton -- t5 On complex adpositions in Modern Greek -- t6 Complex prepositions in Albanian: A first assessment -- tNon Indo-European languages -- t7 What makes a complex postposition: The cyclic development of postpositions in Estonian -- t8 Complex and simple postpositions: The split in Permic -- t9 Case marking and complex adpositions in Basque -- t10 Structure and origin of Turkish adpositions -- t11 A chapter on compound prepositions in Maltese: prep-prep combinations and related issues -- tDiscussion -- t12 Complex adpositions in Europe and beyond: A synthesis -- tIndex -- tLanguage Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile much attention has been devoted to simple nominal relators, especially prepositions and case markers, complex nominal relators have not yet been the focus of a systematic and cross-linguistic study.The chapters of this volume provide not only a working definition of such constructions, but also a description of complex adpositions and other complex nominal relators in a variety of European languages, both Indo-European and non-Indo-European, including some languages for which this phenomenon had received little attention, such as Breton and Albanian. Building on synchronic and diachronic corpus-based investigations, the authors show commonalities and specificities of these linguistic items across languages, trying to explain why and how they emerged.The research presented in this volume confirms the wide-spread use of complex adpositions in Europe, and the data reviewed in the final discussion suggests it might be the same in other parts of the world, as well. This book thus offers not only detailed descriptions of complex nominal relators in fifteen languages, but also indications of what to look for in other languages, and how to distinguish between a syntactically free sequence and a genuine complex nominal relator.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aAdpositions.  aConstructionalization.  aCorpus Studies.  aGrammaticalization.1 aArkhangelskiy, Timofey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonnet, Guillaume, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBortone, Pietro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFagard, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFagard, Benjamin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHüning, Matthias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re